Making Smart Thermostats Smarter

Using Classification for Inference and Prediction

Ecobee provides donated customer datasets on its website, allowing for analytics on large smart thermostat datasets. This dataset contains records for thermostat readings for every five minutes for one year, starting January first. Continuous predictor fields include outoor temperature and humidity, indoor average temperature and humidity, the cool and heat setpoints, and the categorical fields of Event and Schedule. The response variable is Override, indicating if the user has changed the set point temperature from the what the smart thermostat has selected.

The smart thermostat sets the indoor temperature based on preprogramming. Building statistical models to predict whether the user will override the set temperature will create pathways to improve smart thermostat performance.

NOTE: There is no indication of the geolocation of the home where the data was collected, so outdoor environmental factors are considered out of the context of local weather, and notes are given where assumptions are made based on the location of the home during the exploratory and visualization portions of the project.

Training/Testing Split

The data will be split randomly, using 90% of the original dataset for training and 10% for model testing and performance validation. While the dataset is indexed using a date-time stamp, it will not be strictly treated as a time series. To do so would require further data -- the following year -- to recognize cyclical patterns, and to test model accuracy on a similar timeframe. Since the data contains exactly one year of records, a predictive model trained on data from January to August would likely perform poorly when tested against hold-out data from September to December. Using 90% of the 105,120 records will provide enough data to allow for accurate inference of cyclical or time-specific patterns that are present in the dataset as a whole.

The training and test set will be stratified so that there is a balanced representation of the response in both sets, avoiding potential issues where the positive case of the response is randomly over-represented in one set and rarely present in another.

The baseline accuracy is 0.8325

Any model should perform better than a 0.8325 accuracy on the training data. Because the test data was stratified, there will be a similar baseline performance expectation.

We must also be mindful of the inbalance of the response -- only 16.75% of the records contain a positive response variable. That is, the thermostat is rarely overridden by the user, so it may be difficult to find clear instances from the predictor variables where it is likely the override is used.

Using the frequency distribution of the Indoor_CoolSetpoint, it is likely the smart thermostat is setting the temperature to 71 or 76. Looking at the Cross tabulation of override occurrences at each temperature setting, we see that the temperature is rarely overridden at 71 or 76. At higher set points, the thermostat is rarely overridden (only 5 times in 4844 records where the cool set point was overridden to 80). When the Cool setting is set at a warmer temperature, the homeowner adjusts, or overrides, the thermostat less frequently.

At the other end of the temperature range, most cool set points have been overridden. When the Cool setpoint is at a lower temperature, the homeowner overrides the setting at higher frequency.

Some consideration should be given to the fact that the temperature setpoints may be the result of an override. Using randomly split data removes the ability to look at the sequences of data where an override is active and the setpoint changed from one value to another, or that the average temperature changed to represent the new setpoint. But looking at the above crosstabulation, we see the relationship between the cool setpoint and the frequency of overrides, a relationship that was absent when looking at a similar distribution for the continuous outdoor data.

A similar pattern emerges for the Heat setpoint: when the thermostat sets a warmer temperature, the homeowner overrides the selection at a much higher frequency.

The mean set temperature varies little from month to month. Because the thermostat is not overridden most of the time, these mean temperatures can be assumed to be what the thermostat is setting and not a result of an override by the user.

A feature could be engineered that looked at the absolute difference between the mean (or median) set temperature and the actual set temperature, but consideration would have to be given to time of year and outdoor temperatures to determine if the field would use the Indoor_CoolSetpoint or the Indoor_HeatSetpoint. A value is recorded for each record no matter the time of year, but the Indoor_CoolSetpoint is unlikely to influence a temperature change in winter.

Temperature and Humidity Difference

We can use the differnce between the outside temperature and the indoor average temperature (measured over the last five minutes for each record) to see if it is more likely the thermostat will be overridden. For example, if it is much hotter outside than the average indoor temperature, will the user change the set temperature by overriding the thermostat?

Hourly Statistics

Is there a higher frequency of overrides based on the hour of the day? If the user comes home from work, will they change the setting? When they get out of bed?

In[60]:
hour_data = {
    "Hour": X_train["date_time"].dt.hour,
    "Override":y_train_encoded
}

hour_df = pd.DataFrame(hour_data)
In[62]:
hour_df.groupby("Hour")["Override"].sum().plot(kind = "bar")

plt.title("Overrides by Hour")

plt.show()

We do see a higher total override during the afternoon -- from 3 PM to 8 PM. I am surprised by the overrides that occur during the four hours after midnight. This leads me to believe that an "Override" isn't an instance of button push, but for each record (a five minute interval) an override occurs if the set temperature is different than some prescribed setting by the smart thermostat. So if the thermostat is overridden at 8 PM and is kept at that new temperature for an hour, there will be a total of 12 instances of "Override" in the data set. We don't know when the thermostat reverts back to an non-overridden state, even as the average indoor temperature changes because the set temperature has been manually changed.

This will lead to some unreliability when using the indoor measurements, as "Override" is still being recorded despite the environment changing.

Will there be more overrides on the weekend?

plt.xlabel("")
plt.ylabel("")

The "Override" occurred significantly fewer times on weekends compared to weekdays. Fridays had the highest occurence of overrides, followed by Wednesday.

Perhaps the thermostat is programmed for a single temperature on weekends, whereas on weekdays there are multiple settings programmed. If no one is home during the workday, a more energy efficient temperature can be set, but when someone comes home, this setting is manually overridden. On weekends a single, perhaps more comfortable, temperature setting is used for the whole day and is less likely to be changed.

Feature Engineering

What features do you think will be most important in your model and why? These can be either provided or engineered features. Then, try to be creative in coming up with an expansive set of features to provide to your model. Finally, what features do you think would improve your model that you don't have access to currently and, if you had more time, how would you go about collecting that data?

Features will be added to represent the hour of the day and the day of the week. The EDA of the training data showed that these features show relationships with the override setting. The time features will be additionally engineered to represent the cyclical nature of the predictor field -- sine and cosine.

In[116]:
# Extract time components
X_train['hour'] = X_train['date_time'].dt.hour
X_train['day_of_week'] = X_train['date_time'].dt.dayofweek

# Cyclical encoding
X_train['hour_sin'] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * X_train['hour'] / 24)
X_train['hour_cos'] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * X_train['hour'] / 24)
X_train['day_sin'] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * X_train['day_of_week'] / 7)
X_train['day_cos'] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * X_train['day_of_week'] / 7)

Interactions between indoor temperature and humidity and outdoor temperature and humidity will be included. With these features we ask whether the relationship between the temperature and the level of humidity influenced the decision to override the thermostat.

In[120]:
X_train['id_temp_humidity'] = X_train['Indoor_AverageTemperature']*X_train['Indoor_Humidity']
X_train['od_temp_humidity'] = X_train['Outdoor_Temperature']*X_train['Outdoor_Humidity']

We can also ask if the absolute difference between the outdoor and indoor temperature has any influence on the likelihood of the override being pressed.

In[124]:
X_train['temp_diff'] = abs(X_train['Indoor_AverageTemperature'] - X_train['Outdoor_Temperature'])

Because the "Event" predictor field had no relation to the response -- at no time when an Event was programmed into the thermostat was it overridden -- the field will be dropped.

Second Model - Selection and Fitting

A random forest classification ensemble model will be built with the goal of predicting when the thermostat Override is engaged. Cross validation will be used to determine the best set of hyperparameters. Randomized Search Cross Validation is used to reduce computing demands.

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV


param_dist_rf = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'max_depth': [10, 15, 20, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],
    'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2']
}

rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=30, n_jobs=-1)
rf_random = RandomizedSearchCV(rf, param_dist_rf, 
                               n_iter=100, 
                               cv=5,  
                               scoring='accuracy', 
                               n_jobs=1, 
                               verbose=2,
                               random_state=20)

rf_random.fit(rf_features, y_train_encoded)

best_rf = rf_random.best_estimator_
rf_preds = best_rf.predict(rf_features)

rf_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train_encoded, rf_preds)

print(f"Accuracy: {rf_accuracy: .4f}")
print(f"\nBest Parameters:")
for param, value in rf_random.best_params_.items():
    print(f"  {param}: {value}")

Conclusion

If our goal is to make the smart thermostat smarter, then the best model to put into production would be the logistic regression model. The logistic regression model produces coefficients that the thermostat can use to make adjustments. For this particular data set, when the thermostat sets itself at a lower temperature during the summer months, the more likely it would be overridden; the higher the temperature setting, the less likely an override by the user. A similar pattern emerged with the heat setting: the higher the heat setting the more likely the occurrence of an override. To put it simply: the customer likes it a little warmer in the summer and a little cooler in the winter. Whether this is a case of personal comfort or minding cost, we cannot say. But the logistic model will allow the agent to be trainable. It can learn that if the temperature setting is at a certain point at a specific time during a particular part of the year its okay to tick up the cool setting in the summer and tick down the heat setting during the winter.

Using a logistic model there is less of a penalty for predicting a false positive for the overridewe only need enough override signals to teach the thermostat to make adjustments, not to be right every time. The random forest model validates the prediction patterns, and supplies feature importance values that support the logistic model, but it doesnt give the likelihood of an override.

By creating the two models I learned that, while important, a model that is 100% accurate isnt always better when it comes to training an AI agent. The random forest model was very accurate and was able to show how it made its decisions, but not why certain features were important, just that they were. The logistic model, while not as accurate, was able to show specific trends in the data that would allow an AI agent to act on its environment.

The ecobee thermostat is actually very smart, as evidenced by the relatively few overrides for the data set (only 16.75 % of the records were overrides). We must remember that a record in the data with an instance of an override doesnt represent a single button push by the homeowner, but all the time that the thermostat was in an overridden state (divided into five minute increments). If we were to apply the 16% override rate to a 365-day calendar, we can make the naive estimate that throughout the year the thermostat is overridden only 58 times if adjusted once perg to bed.

Final Analysis

Considering the exploratory data analysis, it is likely that this particular home owner was likely overriding the thermostat with the intention to save on cost, adjusting the cool setting up in the summer and the warm setting down in the winter, making adjustments in the morning before leaving for work and again in the evening before going
